map_node.indicator_description:
People who are threatened with eviction, even before they lose their home, are more likely to report poor health, high blood pressure, depression, anxiety, and psychological distress. Eviction often leads to residential instability, moving into poor quality housing, overcrowding, and homelessness, all of which is associated with negative health among adults and children.

(From "The Hidden Health Crisis of Eviction" by Allison Bovell-Ammo and Megan Sandel)

dataset.how_calculated:
Rate of evictions ordered by the New York City Housing Court and executed by New York City Marshals, including those pending and scheduled as of December 31, per 10,000 housing units. Note: Reported rate is an underestimate, because it might not include every eviction executed by every Marshal, and does not include evictions executed by county sherriffs.

Eviction data are reported by New York City Marshals and gathered from NYC Open Data. For more information, see: https://data.cityofnewyork.us/City-Government/Evictions/6z8x-wfk4
dataset.discription: New York City Department of Investigation

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.

Link.y_axis_title: Estimated Annual Rate (per 10,000 homes) (Median of Neighborhoods)

info.info_how_calculated: Neighborhoods are ranked according to the percent of people whose annual income falls below 100% of the federal poverty level. Rankings are then divided into 3 approximately equal groupings of low, medium and high poverty.
